body: Not sure what you mean by "standard" interface. It's not the same as ONNXIFI. We don't transform the graph into any new format. The GetCapability API returns a subset of the graph that it is capable of executing in the form of node ids. ONNX Runtime marks this subset with this provider (see SetExecutionProvider in the node API) and then moves on to the next provider in the preference order for partitioning. Check graph_partitioning.cc.

Thanks for your quick feedback.  The  "standard" interface means that is defined by an alliance, such as ONNX or other organizations, and we can find the specific interface specification. In addtion,  would you like to tell us where to find the detaied interface document between Onnx Runtime and Execution Provider?

We've some documentation here https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/docs/AddingExecutionProvider.md. We're actively working with several execution providers and will continue to refine the interface as the need arises.
After checking your link I couldn't find the detailed description about interface defintion, maybe I need to check the source code? Pls clarify it again, looking forward to receiving your feedback.

The interface file is linked on the page I mentioned before. This is the best we've today.
https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/include/onnxruntime/core/framework/execution_provider.h. We work closely with providers to ensure a smooth integration.
@Rice-guan ONNX Runtime has internal graph IR. It sends graph(internal IR format) to the execution provider.
Please reopen if you've any more questions. Thanks!

It may sound like  an oxymoron.  "Onnx Runtime doesn't  transform the graph into any new format. " and ONNX Runtime has internal graph IR. Would you like to clarify again?   In addition,  Onnx Runtime will tansform initial input graph(ONNX format) into TVM graph through compiler according to the source code and notes?

ONNX runtime is the runtime for models in the ONNX format. ONNX is a representation of the model (graph) in protobuf format. This is converted into an in-memory representation by the ONNX runtime - which we're calling as internal graph IR. This is the format used internally inside the runtime for performing graph transformations like operator fusion, constant folding, etc. These are internal transformations and the graph format remains the same after them. The TVM stuff is not fully developed yet; hence I wouldn't worry about it for now. Hope this clarifies.

Hi, exploring onnx and it's RT space. Any help/thoughts on below is highly appreciable.

- What is an Execution Provider from ONNX Runtime perspective? 
- It is reasonable to call CPU and GPU as EPs, but why Intel Openvino, TensorRTs, etc are called EPs?
- How is an Execution Provider different from ONNX Runtime?
- Isn't it possible to use standalone execution providers (only TensorRT, without onnx runtime)? 
- How is using onnx runtime being advantageous along with EPs?
- How is onnx runtime different from TVM Compiler?

> Hi, exploring onnx and it's RT space. Any help/thoughts on below is highly appreciable.
> 
> * What is an Execution Provider from ONNX Runtime perspective?
Please see this [design doc](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/docs/InferenceHighLevelDesign.md).

> * It is reasonable to call CPU and GPU as EPs, but why Intel Openvino, TensorRTs, etc are called EPs?
CPU and GPUs are just devices, while openvino, tensorrt are specific EPs that can execute ONNX graphs on these devices.

> * How is an Execution Provider different from ONNX Runtime?
> * Isn't it possible to use standalone execution providers (only TensorRT, without onnx runtime)?
Yes, you can.

> * How is using onnx runtime being advantageous along with EPs?
EPs don't always support the full ONNX standard. Hence it's quite possible that an onnx model might not work on the EPs directly. ORT implements the full ONNX standard and guarantees to execute your model even if EPs cannot do so. It does this by falling back on the CPU implementation of ops. Please read the design doc for more details.

> * How is onnx runtime different from TVM Compiler?
ORT is an inferencing runtime. TVM is a compiler for DNNs. Different objectives.

Also, please open a new issue if you've any further questions/clarifications.

I am further asking the following questions (in a new issue as suggested) with relevance and continuation to the replies in the [comment](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/232#issuecomment-734060575) by @pranavsharma 

- CPU was provided under Execution Providers in the design document. May I understand the reason?

- How is standalone execution provider different from execution provider along with ONNX Runtime?

- Why is the need of hardware independent optimizations (after converting ONNX model to in-memory graph rep) ?

- How are the sub-graphs after partitioning scheduled on to different EPs? Do we need to write a script defining the priorities for scheduling?

- As few execution providers are not having the implementation of few onnx operators, would it be possible to implement those operators in execution providers? (to avoid the fallback onto cpu and hit bad with performance)

Trying to connect all the dots of understanding. Any support with patience is a great help to me. Thank you.
